	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Wii and Dreamcast have a main CPU and an ARM coprocessor.
<br />
<br />In modern PCs, the CPU is either x86 or x86-64. The GPU is a DSP with an unknown architecture, and a program on the CPU called a driver translates OpenGL, shader language, and OpenCL into instructions for the GPU. Various microcontrollers on the network card, sound card, keyboard controller, etc. have their own instruction sets.
<br />
<br />But in fact, the Super NES can have FOUR instruction sets running at once: 65c816, SPC700, Super FX, and some Sharp 4-bit microcontroller.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


